Women in North Korea have traditionally got married and had children at a younger age than their Japanese neighbours, thanks to Marxist tradition. During their teenage years, they reportedly received more secondary education than Japanese girls.^39 Some men are known to have discouraged their daughters from completing the required preliminary conditions to getting a university entrance exam, citing pressure from their wives to send the children to schools elsewhere. It is the wives who get to choose which child they wish to take with them upon becoming divorced.

With over 90% of the textile industry in the country owned by the State and government subsidies prompting strict work discipline over production, women are occupied in the 24-hour work system that involves slow production lines at which they are expected to produce more products whilst simultaneously working in state planning. They certainly do not get the time to think about anything else than the task at hand. Women are considerably close to their families, as they live at their parents’ house until they are married.

Communist Korea’s workplace and ideological perspective reflected women as having a part to play in contributing to the state’s vision of ‘national prestige and material wellbeing’.^40

Guilt and responsibilities

North Korean women get married and divorced according to age, age appropriate or the men chosen for them. Although wife beating (or martial law) was legalised in 1954, much of it was curtailed with a newly enforced law that ended divorce at will
